# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: firebird-db
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:firebird-db/features] The open source Firebird® relational database management system performs excellently and scales impressively, from an embedded, single-user model to enterprise-wide deployments with multiple 2Tb+Gb databases running with hundreds of simultaneous clients.
[src:firebird-db/features] High compatibility with industry standards on many fronts makes Firebird the obvious choice for developing interoperable applications for homogeneous and hybrid environments.
[src:firebird-db/features] The mix of high performance, small footprint, supreme scalability, silent and simple installation and 100% royalty-free deployment make Firebird a highly attractive choice for all types of software developers and vendors.
[src:firebird-db/features] It is used by approximately 1 million of software developers worldwide.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Within a week of the InterBase 6.0 source being released by Borland on 25 July 2000, the Firebird project was created on SourceForge.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird 1.0 was released for Linux, Microsoft Windows and Mac OS X on 11 March 2002, with ports to Solaris, FreeBSD 4, HP-UX over the next two months.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Work on porting the codebase from C to C++ began in 2000.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] On 23 February 2004, Firebird 1.5 was released, which was the first stable release of the new codebase.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Version 1.5 featured an improved query optimizer, SQL-92 conditional expressions, SQL:1999 savepoints and support for explicit locking.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird 2.0 was released on 12 November 2006, adding support for 64-bit architectures, tables nested in FROM clauses, and programmable lock timeouts in blocking transactions.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Version 2.1.6 added new features including procedural triggers, recursive queries, and support for SQL:2003 MERGE statements.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird 2.5 introduced new features like improved multithreading, regular expression syntax and the ability to query remote databases.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird 3.0 was released in 19 April 2016, with a focus in performance and security.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] A major re-architecture of the code allowed total support to SMP machines when using the SuperServer version.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Through the Google Summer of Code 2013 work has begun on integrating Firebird as a replacement for HSQLDB in LibreOffice Base.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] In April 2003, the Mozilla Organization announced a rename of its web browser from *Phoenix* to *Firebird* after a trademark dispute with Phoenix Technologies.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] This decision caused concern within the Firebird database project due to the assumption that users and Internet search engines would be confused by a database and a web browser both using the name Firebird.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The Mozilla developers issued a statement, making clear that their software package was called "Mozilla Firebird", not "Firebird".
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The statement also said that the Mozilla Firebird name was a project codename.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The dispute was resolved on 9 February 2004, when Mozilla changed the name of its browser to Mozilla Firefox, thus ending the conflict.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird inherited the storage architecture of Interbase.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] To ensure the ACID properties of transactions, the database engine keeps different versions of each record changed by the active users in the database.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] When the transactions are committed, the last version of every changed record is marked as the definitive.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] If transactions are rolled back, the database engine keeps the mark on the original record versions, leaving them untouched.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] As a result, Firebird disk writes are very reduced compared to databases that use the traditional transaction log architecture.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Writing transactions does not prevent reading and vice versa, because each one sees its own version of the database.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The tradeoff is that some maintenance ("sweeping") is required from time to time to clean up old record versions and free disk space.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The multi-generational architecture ensures that OLTP and DSS/OLAP operations can be run simultaneously without the delays caused by locking mechanisms found in other products.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird makes all indices of the database behave like well-tuned "clustered indexes" used by other architectures.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Firebird index buckets aren't subject to two-phase locking, and boolean "and" and "or" operations can be performed on intermediate bitmaps at a negligible cost, eliminating the need for the optimizer to choose between alternative indexes.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The Firebird database engine and its modules are released under an open-source license, the Initial Developer's Public License (IDPL), a variant of the Mozilla Public License (MPL) version 1.1.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] It does not require the developer to open the products using Firebird or even custom-derivatives made from its source code, but if the developer chooses to do so, then some terms and conditions should be honored.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The IDPL allows the developer to make proprietary, closed-source applications that use Firebird or are based on it.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The Firebird native API is used directly or indirectly by applications or middleware that connect to a Firebird database.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] It is implemented in the client library, fbclient.dll, on Windows systems, and in libfbclient.so on Unix ones.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] The Services API is a special function set for accessing and controlling service administration tasks such as user management, backup/restore and statistics gathering.
[src:firebird-db/firebird-database-server] Embedded SQL is a technique that simplifies the development of C/C++ and COBOL Firebird applications, by using a preprocessor called gpre, which allows the embedding of SQL statements directly into the source code of the host language.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] InterBase is a SQL-92-compliant relational database and supports standard interfaces such as JDBC, ODBC, and ADO.NET.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Multiversion concurrency control is described in some detail in sections 4.3 and 5.5 of the 1981 paper "Concurrency Control in Distributed Database Systems" by Philip Bernstein and Nathan Goodman while employed by the Computer Corporation of America.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Bernstein and Goodman's paper cites a 1978 dissertation by D.P.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Reed, which describes MVCC and claims it as an original work.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Jim Starkey was working at DEC on their DATATRIEVE 4th generation language 4GL product when he came up with an idea for a system to manage concurrent changes by many users.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] The idea simplified the existing problems of *locking* which were proving to be a serious problem for the new relational database systems being developed at the time.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] In early 2000, Borland announced that InterBase would be released under open-source, and began negotiations to spin off a separate company to manage the product.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] The source code for InterBase version 6 was released under a variant of the Mozilla Public License in mid-2000.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] With the InterBase division at Borland under new management, the company released a proprietary version of InterBase version 6 and then 6.5.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Borland released several updates to the open source code before announcing that it would no longer actively develop the open source project.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] Firebird, an open source fork of the InterBase 6 code, however, remains in active development.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] In 2001, a backdoor was discovered in the software that had been present in all versions since 1994 and then resolved.
[src:firebird-db/interbase] On May 7, 2008, Borland and Embarcadero Technologies announced that Embarcadero had "signed a definitive asset purchase agreement to purchase CodeGear." The acquisition, for approximately $24.5 million, closed on 30 June 2008.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A **relational database** (**RDB**) is a database based on the relational model of data, as proposed by E.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) is a type of database management system that stores data in a structured format using rows and columns.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Many relational database systems are equipped with the option of using SQL (Structured Query Language) for querying and updating the database.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The concept of relational database was defined by E.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Codd introduced the term *relational* in his research paper "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In this paper and later papers, he defined what he meant by *relation*.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] One well-known definition of what constitutes a relational database system is composed of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Provide relational operators to manipulate the data in tabular form.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In 1974, IBM began developing System R, a research project to develop a prototype RDBMS.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The first system sold as an RDBMS was Multics Relational Data Store (June 1976).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Oracle was released in 1979 by Relational Software, now Oracle Corporation.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Other examples of an RDBMS include IBM Db2, SAP Sybase ASE, and Informix.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In 1984, the first RDBMS for Macintosh began being developed, code-named Silver Surfer, and was released in 1987 as 4th Dimension and known today as 4D.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The most common definition of an RDBMS is a product that presents a view of data as a collection of rows and columns, even if it is not based strictly upon relational theory.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] By this definition, RDBMS products typically implement some but not all of Codd's 12 rules.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A second school of thought argues that if a database does not implement all of Codd's rules (or the current understanding on the relational model, as expressed by Christopher J.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Date, Hugh Darwen and others), it is not relational.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] This view, shared by many theorists and other strict adherents to Codd's principles, would disqualify most DBMSs as not relational.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] For clarification, they often refer to some RDBMSs as *truly-relational database management systems* (TRDBMS), naming others *pseudo-relational database management systems* (PRDBMS).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] As of 2009, most commercial relational DBMSs employ SQL as their query language.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Alternative query languages have been proposed and implemented, notably the pre-1996 implementation of Ingres QUEL.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A relational model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type" (such as customer or product).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The rows represent instances of that type of entity (such as "Lee" or "chair") and the columns represent values attributed to that instance (such as address or price).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Each row in a table has its own unique key.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Rows in a table can be linked to rows in other tables by adding a column for the unique key of the linked row (such columns are known as foreign keys).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Codd showed that data relationships of arbitrary complexity can be represented by a simple set of concepts.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Part of this processing involves consistently being able to select or modify one and only one row in a table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Therefore, most physical implementations have a unique primary key (PK) for each row in a table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] When a new row is written to the table, a new unique value for the primary key is generated; this is the key that the system uses primarily for accessing the table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] System performance is optimized for PKs.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Other, more natural keys may also be identified and defined as alternate keys (AK).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Often several columns are needed to form an AK (this is one reason why a single integer column is usually made the PK).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Both PKs and AKs have the ability to uniquely identify a row within a table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Additional technology may be applied to ensure a unique ID across the world, a globally unique identifier, when there are broader system requirements.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The primary keys within a database are used to define the relationships among the tables.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] When a PK migrates to another table, it becomes a foreign key (FK) in the other table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] When each cell can contain only one value and the PK migrates into a regular entity table, this design pattern can represent either a one-to-one or one-to-many relationship.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Most relational database designs resolve many-to-many relationships by creating an additional table that contains the PKs from both of the other entity tables – the relationship becomes an entity; the resolution table is then named appropriately and the two FKs are combined to form a PK.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The migration of PKs to other tables is the second major reason why system-assigned integers are used normally as PKs; there is usually neither efficiency nor clarity in migrating a bunch of other types of columns.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Relationships are a logical connection between different tables (entities), established on the basis of interaction among these tables.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] These relationships can be modelled as an entity-relationship model.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In order for a database management system (DBMS) to operate efficiently and accurately, it must use ACID transactions.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Part of the programming within an RDBMS is accomplished using stored procedures (SPs).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Often procedures can be used to greatly reduce the amount of information transferred within and outside of a system.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] For increased security, the system design may grant access to only the stored procedures and not directly to the tables.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Fundamental stored procedures contain the logic needed to insert new and update existing data.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] More complex procedures may be written to implement additional rules and logic related to processing or selecting the data.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The relational database was first defined in June 1970 by Edgar Codd, of IBM's San Jose Research Laboratory.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Codd's view of what qualifies as an RDBMS is summarized in Codd's 12 rules.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A relational database has become the predominant type of database.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Other models besides the *relational model* include the hierarchical database model and the network model.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In a relational database, a *relation* is a set of tuples that have the same attributes.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A tuple usually represents an object and information about that object.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Objects are typically physical objects or concepts.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A relation is usually described as a table, which is organized into rows and columns.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] All the data referenced by an attribute are in the same domain and conform to the same constraints.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The relational model specifies that the tuples of a relation have no specific order and that the tuples, in turn, impose no order on the attributes.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Applications access data by specifying queries, which use operations such as *select* to identify tuples, *project* to identify attributes, and *join* to combine relations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Relations can be modified using the *insert*, *delete*, and *update* operators.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] New tuples can supply explicit values or be derived from a query.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Similarly, queries identify tuples for updating or deleting.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] If the tuple contains a candidate or primary key then obviously it is unique; however, a primary key need not be defined for a row or record to be a tuple.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The definition of a tuple requires that it be unique, but does not require a primary key to be defined.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Because a tuple is unique, its attributes by definition constitute a superkey.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] All data are stored and accessed via relations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Relations that store data are called "base relations", and in implementations are called "tables".
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Other relations do not store data, but are computed by applying relational operations to other relations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] These relations are sometimes called "derived relations".
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In implementations these are called "views" or "queries".
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Derived relations are convenient in that they act as a single relation, even though they may grab information from several relations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Also, derived relations can be used as an abstraction layer.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A domain describes the set of possible values for a given attribute, and can be considered a constraint on the value of the attribute.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Mathematically, attaching a domain to an attribute means that any value for the attribute must be an element of the specified set.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The character string *"ABC"*, for instance, is not in the integer domain, but the integer value *123* is.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Another example of domain describes the possible values for the field "CoinFace" as ("Heads","Tails").
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] So, the field "CoinFace" will not accept input values like (0,1) or (H,T).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Constraints are often used to make it possible to further restrict the domain of an attribute.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] For instance, a constraint can restrict a given integer attribute to values between 1 and 10.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Constraints provide one method of implementing business rules in the database and support subsequent data use within the application layer.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] SQL implements constraint functionality in the form of check constraints.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Constraints restrict the data that can be stored in relations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] These are usually defined using expressions that result in a Boolean value, indicating whether or not the data satisfies the constraint.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Constraints can apply to single attributes, to a tuple (restricting combinations of attributes) or to an entire relation.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Since every attribute has an associated domain, there are constraints (**domain constraints**).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The two principal rules for the relational model are known as **entity integrity** and **referential integrity**.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Every relation/table has a primary key, this being a consequence of a relation being a set.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A primary key uniquely specifies a tuple within a table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] While natural attributes (attributes used to describe the data being entered) are sometimes good primary keys, surrogate keys are often used instead.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A surrogate key is an artificial attribute assigned to an object which uniquely identifies it (for instance, in a table of information about students at a school they might all be assigned a student ID in order to differentiate them).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The surrogate key has no intrinsic (inherent) meaning, but rather is useful through its ability to uniquely identify a tuple.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Another common occurrence, especially in regard to N:M cardinality is the composite key.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A composite key is a key made up of two or more attributes within a table that (together) uniquely identify a record.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Foreign key refers to a field in a relational table that matches the primary key column of another table.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Foreign keys need not have unique values in the referencing relation.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A foreign key can be used to cross-reference tables, and it effectively uses the values of attributes in the referenced relation to restrict the domain of one or more attributes in the referencing relation.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] A stored procedure is executable code that is associated with, and generally stored in, the database.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Stored procedures usually collect and customize common operations, like inserting a tuple into a relation, gathering statistical information about usage patterns, or encapsulating complex business logic and calculations.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Frequently they are used as an application programming interface (API) for security or simplicity.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Implementations of stored procedures on SQL RDBMS's often allow developers to take advantage of procedural extensions (often vendor-specific) to the standard declarative SQL syntax.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Stored procedures are not part of the relational database model, but all commercial implementations include them.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] An index is one way of providing quicker access to data.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Indices can be created on any combination of attributes on a relation.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Queries that filter using those attributes can find matching tuples directly using the index (similar to Hash table lookup), without having to check each tuple in turn.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] This is analogous to using the index of a book to go directly to the page on which the information you are looking for is found, so that you do not have to read the entire book to find what you are looking for.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Relational databases typically supply multiple indexing techniques, each of which is optimal for some combination of data distribution, relation size, and typical access pattern.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Indices are usually implemented via B+ trees, R-trees, and bitmaps.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Indices are usually not considered part of the database, as they are considered an implementation detail, though indices are usually maintained by the same group that maintains the other parts of the database.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The use of efficient indexes on both primary and foreign keys can dramatically improve query performance.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] This is because B-tree indexes result in query times proportional to log(n) where n is the number of rows in a table and hash indexes result in constant time queries (no size dependency as long as the relevant part of the index fits into memory).
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Queries made against the relational database, and the derived relvars in the database are expressed in a relational calculus or a relational algebra.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] In his original relational algebra, Codd introduced eight relational operators in two groups of four operators each.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Other operators have been introduced or proposed since Codd's introduction of the original eight including relational comparison operators and extensions that offer support for nesting and hierarchical data, among others.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Normalization was first proposed by Codd as an integral part of the relational model.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] It encompasses a set of procedures designed to eliminate non-simple domains (non-atomic values) and the redundancy (duplication) of data, which in turn prevents data manipulation anomalies and loss of data integrity.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The most common forms of normalization applied to databases are called the normal forms.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database".
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] RDBMS is an extension of that initialism that is sometimes used when the underlying database is relational.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] An alternative definition for a **relational database management system** is a database management system (DBMS) based on the relational model.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Most databases in widespread use today are based on this model.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] RDBMSs have been a common option for the storage of information in databases used for financial records, manufacturing and logistical information, personnel data, and other applications since the 1980s.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Relational databases have often replaced legacy hierarchical databases and network databases, because RDBMS were easier to implement and administer.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] However, due to the expanse of technologies, such as horizontal scaling of computer clusters, NoSQL databases have recently become popular as an alternative to RDBMS databases.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM in the period 1988 to 1994.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] DRDA enables network connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:firebird-db/relational-database] According to research company Gartner, in 2011, the five leading proprietary software relational database vendors by revenue were Oracle (48.8%), IBM (20.2%), Microsoft (17.0%), SAP including Sybase (4.6%), and Teradata (3.7%).
[src:firebird-db/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:firebird-db/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:firebird-db/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:firebird-db/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:firebird-db/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:firebird-db/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:firebird-db/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:firebird-db/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:firebird-db/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:firebird-db/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:firebird-db/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:firebird-db/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:firebird-db/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:firebird-db/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:firebird-db/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:firebird-db/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:firebird-db/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:firebird-db/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:firebird-db/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:firebird-db/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:firebird-db/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:firebird-db/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:firebird-db/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:firebird-db/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:firebird-db/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:firebird-db/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:firebird-db/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:firebird-db/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:firebird-db/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:firebird-db/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
